Why We're Here¶

Photo sharing and photo storage services like to have location data for each photo that is uploaded. With the location data, these services can build advanced features, such as automatic suggestion of relevant tags or automatic photo organization, which help provide a compelling user experience. Although a photo's location can often be obtained by looking at the photo's metadata, many photos uploaded to these services will not have location metadata available. This can happen when, for example, the camera capturing the picture does not have GPS or if a photo's metadata is scrubbed due to privacy concerns.

If no location metadata for an image is available, one way to infer the location is to detect and classify a discernible landmark in the image. Given the large number of landmarks across the world and the immense volume of images that are uploaded to photo sharing services, using human judgement to classify these landmarks would not be feasible.

In this notebook, you will take the first steps towards addressing this problem by building models to automatically predict the location of the image based on any landmarks depicted in the image. At the end of this project, your code will accept any user-supplied image as input and suggest the top k most relevant landmarks from 50 possible landmarks from across the world. The image below displays a potential sample output of your finished project.

Question 1: Describe your chosen procedure for preprocessing the data.

  • How does your code resize the images (by cropping, stretching, etc)? What size did you pick for the input tensor, and why?
  • Did you decide to augment the dataset? If so, how (through translations, flips, rotations, etc)? If not, why not?

Answer: I have applied a resize of all the images to 240x240 pixels in order to be sure that all the loaded images have the same scale and then the convolutional neural network can handle all the batches pretty consistently and without errors, at the same time I have cropped the resized image from the center to assure that the algorithms will focus on the characteristics that were relevant to person that took the photograph.

I have decided to try some data augmentation techniques, so the neural net can generalize better over the image dataset. I have used mainly two techniques a random rotation of 10 degrees and a random change in contrast (that is applied with a probability of 20%). The first one is intended to get more data with slightly changes in orientation and the second one is for changes in the ilumination of the photo scene.

An important fact about the preprocessing of the images converted to tensors is that, as a final preprocessing step, is necessary to normalize the tensors, so the neural net would improve in its patterns identification and finally achieving a good accuracy.

Create a CNN to classify images of landmarks. Use the template in the code cell below.

# define the CNN architecture
class Net(nn.Module):
    ## TODO: choose an architecture, and complete the class
    def __init__(self):
        super(Net, self).__init__()
        
        ## Define layers of a CNN
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 16, 3, padding=1)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(16, 32, 3, padding=1)
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(32, 64, 3, padding=1)
        self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(64, 128, 3, padding=1)
        
        self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)

        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(15 * 15 * 128, 1024)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(1024, 512)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(512, 50)

        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(p=0.3)      
        
    
    def forward(self, x):
        ## Define forward behavior
        x = F.relu(self.conv1(x))
        x = self.maxpool(x)
        x = F.relu(self.conv2(x))
        x = self.maxpool(x)
        x = F.relu(self.conv3(x))
        x = self.maxpool(x)
        x = F.relu(self.conv4(x))
        x = self.maxpool(x)
        x = x.view(-1, 15 * 15 * 128)
        x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = F.relu(self.fc2(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.fc3(x)      
        
        return x

#-#-# Do NOT modify the code below this line. #-#-#

# instantiate the CNN
model_scratch = Net()

# move tensors to GPU if CUDA is available
if use_cuda:
    model_scratch.cuda()

Question 2: Outline the steps you took to get to your final CNN architecture and your reasoning at each step.

Answer:

As described in the course materials and in the different bibliography that is available on Internet, for getting a good classification neural net is important to obtain the features map of the images progressively, for that is necessary to stack convolutional layers that will increase the depth of the feature maps with pooling layers that will provide the mechanisms to discard not important features and focus in the relevant ones. The limit for the number of the stacked layers is the final sizing of the feature map, we can not get to negative scales, and also that a high number of layers will tend to overfit the model during training.

So, in our case I have used 4 convolutional layers with a kernel size of 3 and padding 1, so at the output of the layer is the same size but with different depth depending on the size of the used filter (I have used from 16 to 128), the pooling layer is a Maxpooling one with a kernel size of 2 and a stride of 2, that will get the maximum value of the different pixels that are under the pooling kernel in a certain step of the pooling.

The output of the convolutional/pooling stack is fed to a fully connected layers, but for doing that we need to flatten the tensor, once we have done that we fed it to the dense layers, beginning with 1024 nodes and finishing in 50 (number of classes we need to classify). In between these dense layers I havee applied dropout (30% of probability) to avoid overfitting.

The activation function used for all the layers, but the last one, has been a ReLU activation function.

def train(n_epochs, loaders, model, optimizer, criterion, use_cuda, save_path):
    """returns trained model"""
    # initialize tracker for minimum validation loss
    valid_loss_min = np.Inf 
    
    for epoch in range(1, n_epochs+1):
        # initialize variables to monitor training and validation loss
        train_loss = 0.0
        valid_loss = 0.0
        
        ###################
        # train the model #
        ###################
        # set the module to training mode
        model.train()
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['train']):
            # move to GPU
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()

            ## TODO: find the loss and update the model parameters accordingly
            ## record the average training loss, using something like
            ## train_loss = train_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data.item() - train_loss))
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            output = model(data)
            loss_tr = criterion(output, target)
            loss_tr.backward()
            optimizer.step()

            train_loss = train_loss + ((1 /(batch_idx + 1)) * (loss_tr.item() - train_loss))

        ######################    
        # validate the model #
        ######################
        # set the model to evaluation mode
        model.eval()
        for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['valid']):
            # move to GPU
            if use_cuda:
                data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()

            ## TODO: update average validation loss 
            output = model(data)
            loss_test = criterion(output, target)
            valid_loss = valid_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx +1)) * (loss_test.item() - valid_loss))
            
            

        # print training/validation statistics 
        print('Epoch: {} \tTraining Loss: {:.6f} \tValidation Loss: {:.6f}'.format(
            epoch, 
            train_loss,
            valid_loss
            ))

        ## TODO: if the validation loss has decreased, save the model at the filepath stored in save_path
        
        if valid_loss < valid_loss_min:
            print('Validation loss has descreased ({:.6f}-->{:.6f}). Saving model...'.format(valid_loss_min, valid_loss))
            torch.save(model.state_dict(), save_path)
            valid_loss_min = valid_loss

        
        
    return model

def custom_weight_init(m):
    ## TODO: implement a weight initialization strategy
    class_name = m.__class__.__name__

    if class_name.find('Linear') != -1:
        n = m.in_features
        y = (1 / np.sqrt(n))
        m.weight.data.uniform_(-y, y)
        m.bias.data.fill_(0)

def test(loaders, model, criterion, use_cuda):

    # monitor test loss and accuracy
    test_loss = 0.
    correct = 0.
    total = 0.

    # set the module to evaluation mode
    model.eval()

    for batch_idx, (data, target) in enumerate(loaders['test']):
        # move to GPU
        if use_cuda:
            data, target = data.cuda(), target.cuda()
        # forward pass: compute predicted outputs by passing inputs to the model
        output = model(data)
        # calculate the loss
        loss = criterion(output, target)
        # update average test loss 
        test_loss = test_loss + ((1 / (batch_idx + 1)) * (loss.data.item() - test_loss))
        # convert output probabilities to predicted class
        pred = output.data.max(1, keepdim=True)[1]
        # compare predictions to true label
        correct += np.sum(np.squeeze(pred.eq(target.data.view_as(pred))).cpu().numpy())
        total += data.size(0)
            
    print('Test Loss: {:.6f}\n'.format(test_loss))

    print('\nTest Accuracy: %2d%% (%2d/%2d)' % (
        100. * correct / total, correct, total))

# load the model that got the best validation accuracy
model_scratch.load_state_dict(torch.load('model_scratch.pt'))
test(loaders_scratch, model_scratch, criterion_scratch, use_cuda)

train_transfer_transform = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize((240,240)), transforms.CenterCrop(240), 
                                        transforms.RandomRotation(10), 
                                        transforms.RandomAutocontrast(p=0.2),

train_transfer_data = torchvision.datasets.ImageFolder(train_path, train_transfer_transform)
test_transfer_data = torchvision.datasets.ImageFolder(test_path, test_transfer_transform)

num_train = len(train_transfer_data)
indices = list(range(num_train))
np.random.shuffle(indices)
split = int(np.floor(valid_size * num_train))
train_idx, valid_idx = indices[split:], indices[:split]

train_transfer_sampler = SubsetRandomSampler(train_idx)
valid_transfer_sampler = SubsetRandomSampler(valid_idx)

train_transfer_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_transfer_data, batch_size=batch_transfer_size, sampler=train_transfer_sampler, num_workers=num_workers)
valid_transfer_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_transfer_data, batch_size=batch_transfer_size, sampler=valid_transfer_sampler, num_workers=num_workers)
test_transfer_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(test_transfer_data, batch_size=batch_transfer_size, num_workers=num_workers)


loaders_transfer = {'train': train_transfer_loader, 'valid': valid_transfer_loader, 'test': test_transfer_loader}

## TODO: Specify model architecture

model_transfer = torchvision.models.vgg16(pretrained=True)

# Freeze parameters of convolution layers from imported model.
for param in model_transfer.features.parameters():
    param.requires_grad = False

# Change fully connected layers to the ones that we need for our problem

n_inputs = model_transfer.classifier[6].in_features

new_layer = nn.Linear(n_inputs, 50)

model_transfer.classifier[6] = new_layer

#-#-# Do NOT modify the code below this line. #-#-#

if use_cuda:
    model_transfer = model_transfer.cuda()

Question 3: Outline the steps you took to get to your final CNN architecture and your reasoning at each step. Describe why you think the architecture is suitable for the current problem.

Answer:

I got the VGG16 model pretrained, this model is a classification model trained over the ImageNet dataset and it is able to classify over 1000 different classes. This model is based on many convolutional layers stacked with maxpooling layers, all these layers are able to extract the features of the objects represented in the images, the classification task is done by the last fully connected layers.

Using transfer learning based on this VGG16 model can be done taking advantage of all the convolutional layers and just changing the final fully connected layer to adapt the output of the model to our current problem of classifying landmarks. This can be done, in my opinion, because the images that we are trying to classify have many common elements with the ImageNet dataset.

For doing the transfer learning I downloaded the VGG16 model pretrained, then I fixed the parameters of the feature extraction layers as not trainable to be sure that all the prior training from ImageNet is used. Then I build a new Linear (fully connected) with 50 outputs instead of 1000, I finally change the last layer inserting this new one that I have just defined. I have also adapted the transformations done during the image loading in order to put the same normalization that was used during the training of the VGG16 model.

import cv2
from PIL import Image

## the class names can be accessed at the `classes` attribute
## of your dataset object (e.g., `train_dataset.classes`)

def predict_landmarks(img_path, k):
    ## TODO: return the names of the top k landmarks predicted by the transfer learned CNN
    img = Image.open(img_path)
    convert_tensor = transforms.Compose([transforms.Resize((240,240)), transforms.CenterCrop(240), transforms.ToTensor(), transforms.Normalize((0.485, 0.456, 0.406),(0.229, 0.224, 0.225))])
    tensor = convert_tensor(img)
    tensor.unsqueeze_(0)

    if use_cuda:
        tensor = tensor.cuda()
    
    model_transfer.eval()

    output = model_transfer(tensor)

    values, index = torch.topk(output, k, dim=1)

    model_transfer.train()
    
    selected_landmarks = []
    for i in index[0].tolist():
        selected_landmarks.append(train_data.classes[i])

    return selected_landmarks

Question 4: Is the output better than you expected :) ? Or worse :( ? Provide at least three possible points of improvement for your algorithm.

Answer:

The accuracy and perfomance of the transfer learning model is better than I would expect with so little modifications to the original VGG16 model (let's remember that I only have changed the final fully connected layer), the model returns good predictions for every test I have done with it. In the other hand the global accuracy is about 75%, it is a good value but it seems that there is some margin for enhancing the model.

  • Some more augmentation techniques can be tried for improving accuracy in the test set.

  • It is observed during training that training loss and validation loss start to diverge pretty early, at epoch 7 or so, then we can try to reduce the size of some of the fully connected layers to low overfitting.

  • Trying to reduce this overfitting, I can also try to reduce batch size. In the bibliography is confirmed that smaller batch sizes drive to a neural network less prone to overfitting.
